[[File:Dorylus helvolus, a, Seringveld.jpg|thumb|right|200px|''[[Dorylus]]'' male alate]] '''Alate''' is an adjective that refers to wings or winglike structures.<ref>{{cite book | last = | first = | authorlink = | title = Collins Dictionary | publisher = Collins | series = | volume = | edition = Seventh | date =2008 | location = | pages =34 | language = English | url = | doi = | id = | isbn = 9780007261123 | mr = | zbl = | jfm = }}</ref> In entomology it usually refers to the winged form of a [[social insect]], especially [[ant]]s or [[termite]]s, though can also be applied to [[aphid]]s and some [[thrips]]. Alate females are typically those destined to become [[gyne]]s (queens), whereas alate males are occasionally referred to as "drones" (or "kings", in the case of termites). However, the existence of reproductives that do ''not'' have wings (e.g., [[ergatoid]] queens and [[gamergate]]s) necessitates a term to distinguish the winged from the wingless reproductive forms. This is an example of [[Polymorphism (biology)|polymorphism]] associated with [[eusociality]]. A "[[wiktionary:dealate|dealate]]" is an adult insect that shed or lost its wings ("dealation").
[[File:Euonymus alatus6.jpg|right|thumb|200px|''[[Euonymus alatus]]'' has wing-like structures on the stems]] In botany '''alate''' refers to winglike structures on some seeds that use wind dispersal or it may be used to describe flattened ridges which run longtitudianally on stems.<ref>{{cite book | last = Harrison | first = Lorraine | authorlink = | title = Latin for Gardeners | publisher = [[Royal Horticultural Society]] | series = | volume = | edition = | date = 2012 | location = | pages = 20 | language = English | url = | doi = | id = | isbn = 9781845337315 | mr = | zbl = | jfm = }}</ref>
