'''Camill Heller''' (26 September 1823 – 25 February 1917) was a [[zoologist]] and [[anatomist]].
Heller was born in Sobochleben ([[Krupka|Soběchleby]]) near [[Teplice|Teplitz]] in [[Bohemia]] (now Teplice, part of the [[Czech Republic]]).<ref>{{cite book |chapter=Heller Kamill |language=German |title=Österreichisches Biographisches Lexikon 1815–1950 (ÖBL). Band 2 |publisher=Verlag der Österreichischen Akademie der Wissenschaften, Wien |year=1959 |pages=260 |trans-title=Austrian Biographical Dictionary |url=http://www.biographien.ac.at/oebl_2/260.pdf |format=[[Portable Document Format|PDF]]}}</ref> He received a doctorate in medical studies in [[Vienna]] in 1849.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tmbl.gu.se/libdb/taxon/personetymol/petymol.h.html |title=Dr. Camill Heller |work=Biographical Etymology of Marine Organism Names |author=Hans G. Hansson |publisher=[[University of Gothenburg|Göteborgs Universitet]]}}</ref> Heller was the 'Professor of Zoology and Comparative Anatomy' at the [[University of Krakow]] in [[Poland]] from 1858 to 1863 and from 1863 until his retirement in 1894 he taught at the [[University of Innsbruck]] in [[Austria]].
Heller primarily specialised in [[crustacean]]s but also worked on [[bryozoa]]ns, [[echinoderm]]s, [[Sea spider|pycnogonids]], and [[tunicate]]s.
