{{EngvarB|date=June 2017}} {{Use dmy dates|date=June 2017}} {{Infobox scientist | name = Jon Blundy | birth_name = Jonathan David Blundy | native_name_lang = | image = <!--(filename only, i.e. without "File:" prefix)--> | imagesize = | alt = | caption = | birth_date = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1961|8|7}} | birth_place = | death_date = <!--{{death date and age |df=yes|YYYY|MM|DD|1961|8|7}} (death date then birth date)--> | death_place = | death_cause = | resting_place = | resting_place_coordinates = <!--{{coord|LAT|LONG|type:landmark|display=inline,title}}--> | other_names = | residence = | citizenship = | nationality = | fields = [[Petrology]] | workplaces = {{Plainlist| * [[University of Bristol]] * [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology|MIT]]}} | patrons = | education = | alma_mater = {{Plainlist| * [[University of Oxford]] (BA) * [[University of Cambridge]] (PhD)}} | thesis_title = The geology of the Southern Adamello Massif, Italy | thesis_url = http://ethos.bl.uk/OrderDetails.do?uin=uk.bl.ethos.235760 | thesis_year = 1989 | doctoral_advisor = | academic_advisors = [[Robert Stephen John Sparks]] | doctoral_students = | notable_students = | known_for = | influences = | influenced = | awards = {{Plainlist| * [[Fellow of the Royal Society|FRS]] (2008) * [[Bigsby Medal]] (2005)}} | spouse = <!--(or | spouses = )--> | partner = <!--(or | partners = )--> | children = | signature = <!--(filename only)--> | signature_alt = | website = {{URL|bristol.ac.uk/earthsciences/people/jon-d-blundy}} | footnotes = }}'''Jonathan David Blundy''' [[Fellow of the Royal Society|FRS]] (born 7 August 1961) is Professor of [[Petrology]] in the Department of Earth Sciences at the [[University of Bristol]].<ref>[http://www.bris.ac.uk/news/2008/212017945328.html New Fellow of the Royal Society, Jon Blundy, Professor of Petrology], University of Bristol</ref><ref>{{Cite journal | doi = 10.1007/BF00306444| title = Calcic amphibole equilibria and a new amphibole-plagioclase geothermometer| journal = Contributions to Mineralogy and Petrology| volume = 104| issue = 2| pages = 208| year = 1990| last1 = Blundy | first1 = J. D. | authorlink1 = Jon Blundy| last2 = Holland | first2 = T. J. B. | authorlink2 = Timothy Holland| bibcode = 1990CoMP..104..208B}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal | doi = 10.1007/BF00310910| title = Non-ideal interactions in calcic amphiboles and their bearing on amphibole-plagioclase thermometry| journal = Contributions to Mineralogy and Petrology| volume = 116| issue = 4| pages = 433| year = 1994| last1 = Holland | first1 = T. | authorlink1 = Timothy Holland| last2 = Blundy | first2 = J. | authorlink2 = Jon Blundy| bibcode = 1994CoMP..116..433H}}</ref><ref>[http://planetearth.nerc.ac.uk/news/story.aspx?id=978 Scientists move closer to predicting volcano hazard], planetearth.nerc.ac.uk</ref><ref>{{Cite journal | doi = 10.1038/372452a0| title = Prediction of crystal–melt partition coefficients from elastic moduli| journal = Nature| volume = 372| issue = 6505| pages = 452| year = 1994| last1 = Blundy | first1 = J. | authorlink1 = Jon Blundy| last2 = Wood | first2 = B. | bibcode = 1994Natur.372..452B}}</ref>
==Education== He is a graduate of [[University College, Oxford]] (B.A., 1980) and [[Trinity Hall, Cambridge]], (PhD, 1989) and a former Kennedy Scholar at the [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]] (1985). He was educated at [[St Paul's School, Brazil]], [[Giggleswick School]] and [[Leeds Grammar School]], where petrologists [[Keith Cox]] and [[Lawrence Wager]] also studied.
==Career== Blundy is most noted for advancing the understanding of how [[magma]]s are generated in the Earth's [[crust (geology)|crust]] and [[mantle (geology)|mantle]] and of the processes that occur in [[volcanoes]] before they erupt. He undertook his PhD research at the [[University of Cambridge]] under the supervision of Professor [[Robert Stephen John Sparks]] on the granites of [[Adamello-Presanella]] in the Italian [[Alps]]. In series of seminal papers with Professor [[Bernard John Wood]] in the 1990s Blundy developed a theory of elastic strain to describe the uptake of [[trace elements]] into the crystal lattices of [[igneous]] minerals. The theory was based on high temperature and pressure experiments on molten rocks, and is now widely used to predict crystal-melt partition coefficients for use in modelling magmatic processes.
Blundy subsequently collaborated with [[Katharine Cashman]] at the [[University of Oregon]] on [[Mount St. Helens]] volcano in the [[Cascade Range]] of northwestern USA. Blundy and Cashman demonstrated the importance of degassing in driving the crystallisation of volatile-bearing magmas, a process that can occur without any attendant cooling. In fact, because of the release of [[latent heat of fusion]], magmas that crystallise by decompression can actually get hotter in the process.{{citation needed|date=May 2016}}
==Awards and honours== Blundy is a recipient of the [[F.W. Clarke Medal]] of the [[Geochemical Society]] (1997), and [[Murchison Fund]] (1998) and the [[Bigsby Medal]] of the [[Geological Society of London]] (2005). He was a [[Fulbright Scholar]] at University of Oregon in 1998, Guest Professor at [[Nagoya University]] in 2007 and elected as a [[List of Fellows of the Royal Society elected in 2008|Fellow of the Royal Society (FRS) in 2008]]. His nomination reads: {{centred pull quote|Jon Blundy has made fundamental contributions to understanding the generation and movement of magma within the earth. The breadth of his work is impressive, ranging from field studies of the emplacement mechanisms of granites and volcanic rocks, through experimental petrology and thermodynamics applied to igneous systems, to study of the oxidation state of the mantle. His most recent programme has combined a wide range of field, analytical, and laboratory skills to quantifying the pressure-temperature paths followed by magmas as they ascend beneath volcanoes, and has cast important new light on the evolution of magmas immediately before major eruptions.<ref name=royal>{{cite web|url=https://collections.royalsociety.org/DServe.exe?dsqIni=Dserve.ini&dsqApp=Archive&dsqDb=Catalog&dsqCmd=show.tcl&dsqSearch=(RefNo==%27EC%2F2008%2F07%27) |title=EC/2008/07: Blundy, Jonathan David |publisher=[[The Royal Society]] |archivedate=19 October 2014 |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20141019194857/https://collections.royalsociety.org/DServe.exe?dsqIni=Dserve.ini&dsqApp=Archive&dsqDb=Catalog&dsqCmd=show.tcl&dsqSearch=(RefNo=='EC/2008/07') |location=London |deadurl=yes |df= }}</ref>}}Blundy was also awarded the [[Royal Society Wolfson Research Merit Award]] in 2011.<ref>http://royalsociety.org/news/latest-round-of-prestigious-Wolfson/</ref>
==Personal life== In 1992, Blundy married Katharine Fawcett (rn1963), from whom he has been separated since 2004. He has a daughter, Lilian (born 1997), a son, Stanley (born 1994) and a step-daughter, Jennifer (born 1989).{{citation needed|date=October 2014}}
