'''Limostatin''' (from [[Limos (mythology)|Limos]], the Greek goddess of starvation) is a [[peptide hormone]] found in [[Drosophila melanogaster]] that suppresses the production and release of [[Insulin]]. The hormone is important in adaptation to starvation conditions, and represents a mechanism by which insulin is negatively regulated.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Alfa|first1=Ronald W.|last2=Park|first2=Sangbin|last3=Skelly|first3=Kathleen-Rose|last4=Poffenberger|first4=Gregory|last5=Jain|first5=Nimit|last6=Gu|first6=Xueying|last7=Kockel|first7=Lutz|last8=Wang|first8=Jing|last9=Liu|first9=Yinghua|last10=Powers|first10=Alvin C.|last11=Kim|first11=Seung K.|title=Suppression of Insulin Production and Secretion by a Decretin Hormone|journal=Cell Metabolism|date=February 2015|volume=21|issue=2|pages=323–333|doi=10.1016/j.cmet.2015.01.006|pmid=25651184|pmc=4349554}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|title=Metabolism: Limostatin—a decretin—suppresses insulin production|journal=Nature Reviews Endocrinology|date=2015-02-17|doi=10.1038/nrendo.2015.20}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Conger|first1=Krista|title=Researchers discover insulin-decreasing hormone in flies, humans|url=http://med.stanford.edu/news/all-news/2015/02/researchers-discover-insulin-decreasing-hormone-in-flies-humans.html|website=Stanford Medicine News Center}}</ref>

