{{Pfam_box | Symbol = Thaumatin | Name = Thaumatin family | image = Thaumatin I 1RQW.png | width = 200 | caption = Ribbon<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Stivala A, Wybrow M, Wirth A, Whisstock JC, Stuckey PJ | title = Automatic generation of protein structure cartoons with Pro-origami | journal = Bioinformatics | volume = 27 | issue = 23 | pages = 3315–6 | date = December 2011 | pmid = 21994221 | doi = 10.1093/bioinformatics/btr575 }}</ref><ref>DeLano Scientific LLC. (2004). [http://pymol.sourceforge.net/newman/user/S0260cartoons.html Cartoon Representations].</ref> diagram of thaumatin I. From {{PDB|1RQW}}. | Pfam= PF00314 | InterPro= IPR001938 | SMART= SM00205 | PROSITE= PDOC00286 | SCOP = 1thu | TCDB = | CDD = cd09215 | OPM family= 168 | OPM protein= 1aun | PDB= | Membranome family = 1336 }} {{infobox protein | Name = '''Thaumatin I ''' | caption = | image = | width = | HGNCid = | Symbol = THM1_THADA | AltSymbols = | EntrezGene = | OMIM = | RefSeq = | UniProt = P02883 | PDB = 1RQW | PDB_supplemental = [http://www.ebi.ac.uk/pdbe/searchResults.html?display=both&term=P02883 More structures] | ECnumber = | Chromosome = | Arm = | Band = | LocusSupplementaryData = }} {{infobox protein | Name = '''Thaumatin II ''' | caption = | image = | width = 200 | HGNCid = | Symbol = THM2_THADA | AltSymbols = | EntrezGene = | OMIM = | RefSeq = | UniProt = P02884 | PDB = | ECnumber = | Chromosome = | Arm = | Band = | LocusSupplementaryData = }}
'''Thaumatin''' (also known as talin) is a low-calorie [[Sugar substitute|sweetener]] and flavour modifier. The protein is often used primarily for its flavour-modifying properties and not exclusively as a sweetener.<ref name="pmid10647344">{{cite journal | vauthors = Green C | title = Thaumatin: a natural flavour ingredient | journal = World Review of Nutrition and Dietetics | volume = 85 | issue = | pages = 129–32 | year = 1999 | pmid = 10647344 | doi = 10.1159/000059716 | isbn = 3-8055-6938-6 | series = World Review of Nutrition and Dietetics }}</ref>
The thaumatins were first found as a mixture of [[protein]]s isolated from the [[katemfe]] [[fruit]] (''[[Thaumatococcus daniellii]]'' Bennett) of west [[Africa]]. Some proteins in the thaumatin family of sweeteners are roughly 2000 times more potent than [[sugar]]. Although very sweet, thaumatin's taste is markedly different from sugar's. The sweetness of thaumatin builds very slowly. Perception lasts a long time, leaving a [[liquorice]]-like aftertaste at high usage levels. Thaumatin is highly water-soluble, stable to heating, and stable under acidic conditions.
== Biological role == Thaumatin production is induced in [[Thaumatococcus daniellii|katemfe]] in response to an attack upon the plant by [[viroid]] pathogens. Several members of the thaumatin protein family display significant ''in vitro'' inhibition of hyphal growth and sporulation by various [[fungi]]. The thaumatin protein is considered a prototype for a pathogen-response protein domain. This thaumatin domain has been found in species as diverse as [[rice]] and ''[[Caenorhabditis elegans]]''. Thaumatins are [[pathogenesis-related (PR) proteins]], which are induced by various agents ranging from ethylene to pathogens, and are structurally diverse and ubiquitous in plants:<ref name="PUB00004556">{{cite journal | vauthors = Ruiz-Medrano R, Jimenez-Moraila B, Herrera-Estrella L, Rivera-Bustamante RF | title = Nucleotide sequence of an osmotin-like cDNA induced in tomato during viroid infection | journal = Plant Molecular Biology | volume = 20 | issue = 6 | pages = 1199–202 | date = December 1992 | pmid = 1463856 | doi = 10.1007/BF00028909 }}</ref> They include thaumatin, osmotin, tobacco major and minor PR proteins, alpha-amylase/trypsin inhibitor, and P21 and PWIR2 soybean and wheat leaf proteins. The proteins are involved in systematically acquired resistance and stress response in plants, although their precise role is unknown.<ref name="PUB00004556" /> Thaumatin is an intensely sweet-tasting protein (on a molar basis about 100,000 times as sweet as sucrose<ref name="PUB00001747">{{cite journal | vauthors = Edens L, Heslinga L, Klok R, Ledeboer AM, Maat J, Toonen MY, Visser C, Verrips CT | title = Cloning of cDNA encoding the sweet-tasting plant protein thaumatin and its expression in Escherichia coli | journal = Gene | volume = 18 | issue = 1 | pages = 1–12 | date = April 1982 | pmid = 7049841 | doi = 10.1016/0378-1119(82)90050-6 }}</ref>) found in the West African shrub ''[[Thaumatococcus daniellii]]'': it is induced by attack by viroids, which are single-stranded unencapsulated RNA molecules that do not code for protein. The thaumatin protein I consists of a single polypeptide chain of 207 residues.
Like other PR proteins, thaumatin is predicted to have a mainly beta structure, with a high content of beta-turns and little helix.<ref name="PUB00004556" /> Tobacco cells exposed to gradually increased salt concentrations develop a greatly increased tolerance to salt, due to the expression of osmotin,<ref name="PUB00004573">{{cite journal | vauthors = Singh NK, Nelson DE, Kuhn D, Hasegawa PM, Bressan RA | title = Molecular Cloning of Osmotin and Regulation of Its Expression by ABA and Adaptation to Low Water Potential | journal = Plant Physiology | volume = 90 | issue = 3 | pages = 1096–101 | date = July 1989 | pmid = 16666857 | pmc = 1061849 | doi = 10.1104/pp.90.3.1096 }}</ref> a member of the PR protein family. Wheat plants attacked by barley powdery mildew express a PR protein (PWIR2), which results in resistance against that infection.<ref name="PUB00004543">{{cite journal | vauthors = Mauch F, Hertig C, Rebmann G, Bull J, Dudler R | title = A wheat glutathione-S-transferase gene with transposon-like sequences in the promoter region | journal = Plant Molecular Biology | volume = 16 | issue = 6 | pages = 1089–91 | date = June 1991 | pmid = 1650615 | doi = 10.1007/BF00016083 }}</ref> The similarity between this PR protein and other PR proteins to the maize alpha-amylase/trypsin inhibitor has suggested PR proteins may act as some form of inhibitor.<ref name="PUB00004543" />
The thaumatin-like proteins isolated from kiwi fruit or apple appear to have their allergenic properties minimally reduced by gastroduodenal digestive processes, but not by heating.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Bublin M, Radauer C, Knulst A, Wagner S, Scheiner O, Mackie AR, Mills EN, Breiteneder H | title = Effects of gastrointestinal digestion and heating on the allergenicity of the kiwi allergens Act d 1, actinidin, and Act d 2, a thaumatin-like protein | journal = Molecular Nutrition & Food Research | volume = 52 | issue = 10 | pages = 1130–9 | date = October 2008 | pmid = 18655003 | doi = 10.1002/mnfr.200700167 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Smole U, Bublin M, Radauer C, Ebner C, Breiteneder H | title = Mal d 2, the thaumatin-like allergen from apple, is highly resistant to gastrointestinal digestion and thermal processing | journal = International Archives of Allergy and Immunology | volume = 147 | issue = 4 | pages = 289–98 | year = 2008 | pmid = 18617748 | doi = 10.1159/000144036 }}</ref>
== Production == [[File:Thaumatin crystal grown in microgravity.jpg|left|upright|thumb|Thaumatin crystal (~1 mm long) grown by liquid–liquid diffusion under microgravity conditions in outer space. Arrow marks nucleation point.<ref>{{cite journal | doi = 10.1038/npjmgrav.2015.10 | title = Microgravity protein crystallization | journal = Npj Microgravity | volume = 1 | pages = 15010 | year = 2015 | last1 = McPherson | first1 = Alexander | last2 = Delucas | first2 = Lawrence James | name-list-format = vanc }}</ref>]] Within West Africa, the katemfe fruit has been locally cultivated and used to flavour foods and beverages for some time. The fruit's seeds are encased in a membranous sac, or [[aril]], that is the source of thaumatin. In the 1970s, [[Tate and Lyle]] began extracting thaumatin from the fruit. In 1990, researchers at [[Unilever]] reported the isolation and sequencing of the two principal proteins found in thaumatin, which they dubbed '''thaumatin I''' and '''thaumatin II'''. These researchers were also able to express thaumatin in [[genetic engineering|genetically engineered]] [[bacteria]].
Thaumatin has been approved as a sweetener in the [[European Union]] (E957), [[Israel]], and [[Japan]]. In the [[United States]], it is [[generally recognized as safe]] as a flavouring agent (FEMA GRAS 3732) but not as a sweetener.
==Crystallization of thaumatin== Since thaumatin crystallizes rapidly and easily in the presence of [[tartrate]] ions, thaumatin-tartrate mixtures are frequently used as model systems to study [[protein crystallization]]. The solubility of thaumatin, its crystal habit, and mechanism of crystal formation are dependent upon the [[chirality]] of precipitant used. When crystallized with L- tartrate, thaumatin forms bipyramidal crystals and displays a solubility that increases with temperature; with D- and meso-tartrate, it forms stubby and prismatic crystals and displays a solubility that decreases with temperature.<ref>{{cite journal|doi=10.1021/cg800616q|title= Effects of Protein Purity and Precipitant Stereochemistry on the Crystallization of Thaumatin|journal= Crystal Growth & Design|volume= 8|issue= 12|pages= 4200|year= 2008|last1= Asherie|first1= Neer|last2= Ginsberg|first2= Charles|last3= Greenbaum|first3= Arieh|last4= Blass|first4= Samuel|last5= Knafo|first5= Sarah | name-list-format = vanc }}</ref> This suggests control of precipitant chirality may be an important factor in protein crystallization in general.
== See also == *[[Curculin]], a sweet protein from Malaysia with taste-modifying activity *[[Miraculin]], a protein from West Africa with taste-modifying activity *[[Monellin]], a sweet protein found in West Africa *[[Stevia]], a 0 calorie sweetener up to 150 times sweeter than sugar
